  "prompt": "How much does an author make per book on a translated version of their novel?",
  "response": "The earnings for an author on a translated book can vary widely, but typically involve:\n\n1. Royalties from translation rights:\n- Usually 8-12% of the cover price for each foreign edition sold\n- Flat fee ranging from $3,000-$15,000 depending on the book's potential market\n- Some contracts include an advance payment against future royalties\n\n2. Factors affecting translation royalties:\n- Size of the foreign book market\n- Popularity of the original book\n- Language/country of translation\n- Publisher's standard rates\n- Author's existing international reputation\n\n3. Typical breakdown:\n- The author receives a percentage\n- The literary agent takes a commission (usually 10-15%)\n- The original publisher and translation publisher also take a share\n\nThe exact amount can differ significantly based on individual book contracts, so authors often negotiate these terms specifically with their representatives.\n\nWould you like me to elaborate on any part of this overview of translation royalties?",
